The enhancement in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi mass spectrum around 7300 MeV exceeds the predicted masses of the 3​S3𝑆3S radial excitations given in Table 4 by 250 MeV, making it challenging to attribute this peak (bump) to an S𝑆S-wave tetraquark.
In Ref. Karliner and Rosner (2020) Karliner and Rosner observed that the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi invariant mass region between 6200 and 7300 MeV is rich in meson-meson and baryon-baryon thresholds that might be responsible for such a complex signal structure. As was observed, the dip around 6750​MeV6750MeV6750\,\mathrm{MeV} might correspond to the opening of the S𝑆S-wave di-χc​0subscript𝜒𝑐0\chi_{c0} channel at ≃6829similar-to-or-equalsabsent6829\simeq 6829 MeV, while the dip around 7200​MeV7200MeV7200\,\mathrm{MeV} could be correlated with the opening of the di-ηc​(2​S)subscript𝜂𝑐2𝑆\eta_{c}(2S) channel at ≃7276similar-to-or-equalsabsent7276\simeq 7276 MeV or Ξc​c​Ξ¯c​csubscriptΞ𝑐𝑐subscript¯Ξ𝑐𝑐\Xi_{cc}\bar{\Xi}_{cc} channel at ≃7244similar-to-or-equalsabsent7244\simeq 7244 MeV. Thus, the observation of the bump at 7300 MeV might only be induced by the opening of the di-ηc​(2​S)subscript𝜂𝑐2𝑆\eta_{c}(2S) or Ξc​c​Ξ¯c​csubscriptΞ𝑐𝑐subscript¯Ξ𝑐𝑐\Xi_{cc}\bar{\Xi}_{cc} channels. Combined information of both the four-body calculation mass predictions Wang et al. (2021); Lü et al. (2020) and exploration of the relevant thresholds in the di-J/ψ𝐽𝜓J/\psi invariant mass Karliner and Rosner (2020), prompts us to avoid interpreting the third peak (bump) as a genuine tetraquark state.

However, we observe that in these studies the numerical values of the wave functions are not reported. Nevertheless, the wave functions calculated at the origin can be extracted from the root mean squared radii in a conventional way.
